<div id="content" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<h2 id="head-d4f945a2abc93d343fd04ee81b381d4e490adf40">Intrinsic Attributes</h2>
<p>
Level 1: Levitate<br>
 Level 4: Dragon ESP<br>
 Level 5: Resist Electricity<br>
 Level 10: Resist Cold<br>
 Level 15: Resist Acid<br>
 Level 17: Flight<br>
 Level 35: Resist Poison<br>
 Level 45: Electricity Immunity 
</p>
<h2 id="head-fce06e20e5f7f74aacccab40b59b75a56c8f7305">Comments</h2>
<p>
The ability to recall out of dungeons instantly will save your life frequently. (However, the mosters can still react in this last turn.) 
</p>
<p>
Frequent use of the lightning bolt ability is nice, but won't be as good as some powerful wands. Thunderlords have a magic device bonus of zero so don't expect to use the best activations with great success(zero failure is not possible with most wands anyway). 
</p>
<p>
In 2.2.7 or 2.3 sticks become only linked to magic device skill; so that thunderlords are equal to everyone in this respect from now on. 
</p>
<p>
The straight road is useful early in the game. But later there is a ring that makes jump gates. (-; 
</p>
<p>
Being a slow leveler will save you from doing the nasty quest at level 45 before you're ready. 
</p>

    <ul>

    <li>
<p>
Actually, you can accept this quest but not do it immediately.  If it is accepted, it can be left as long as the player wishes without Gondolin being destroyed. 
</p>
</li>

    </ul>


<p>
Since alchemists need to gain more XP for items than in takes to make a thunderlord level 50, you might as well play a thunderlord alchemist. 
</p>
<p>
Their great flaw is lack of stealth. Alchemist thunderlords can make artifacts of stealth in the late game to fix that. 
</p>
<h2 id="head-ff11f0da0a4cd245270f188d8a7299b4084d0328">Chatter</h2>
<p>
<a href="./FeathinSilyar">FeathinSilyar</a>:  That comment up there about a ring that makes jump gates...I'm assuming it is talking about Flare, or am I clueless about some other ring?  Looks like a bit of a typo, since Flare by no means makes jump gates. 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./AgEnt">AgEnt</a>:  Hmmm, it activates for "dimension door", which seems to act like a high-level minor displacement, i.e. it makes a jump gate to wherever you want, but doesn't toss you through it. 
</p>
